    "1160746": {
      "title": "The Nagata automorphism is wild",
      "abstract": "It is proved that the well known Nagata automorphism of the polynomial ring in three variables over a field of characteristic zero is wild, that is, it can not be decomposed into a product of elementary automorphisms."
    },
    "33765885": {
      "title": "The tame and the wild automorphisms of polynomial rings in three variables",
      "abstract": "Let C = F [x1, x2, . . . , xn] be the polynomial ring in the variables x1, x2, . . . , xn over a field F , and let AutC be the group of automorphisms of C as an algebra over F . An automorphism Žä Ōłł AutC is called elementary if it has a form Žä : (x1, . . . , xiŌłÆ1, xi, xi+1, . . . , xn) 7ŌåÆ (x1, . . . , xiŌłÆ1, ╬▒xi + f, xi+1, . . . , xn), where 0 6= ╬▒ Ōłł F, f Ōłł F [x1, . . . , xiŌłÆ1, xi+1, . . . , xn]. The subgroup of AutC generated by all the elementary automorphisms is called the tame subgroup, and the elements from this subgroup are called tame automorphisms of C. Non-tame automorphisms of the algebra C are called wild. It is well known [6], [9], [10], [11] that the automorphisms of polynomial rings and free associative algebras in two variables are tame. At present, a few new proofs of these results have been found (see [5], [8]). However, in the case of three or more variables the similar question was open and known as ŌĆ£The generation gap problemŌĆØ [2], [3] or ŌĆ£Tame generators problemŌĆØ [8]. The general belief was that the answer is negative, and there were several candidate counterexamples (see [5], [8], [12], [7], [19]). The best known of them is the following automorphism Žā Ōłł Aut(F [x, y, z]), constructed by Nagata in 1972 (see [12]): Žā(x) = x+ (x ŌłÆ yz)z, Žā(y) = y + 2(x ŌłÆ yz)x+ (x ŌłÆ yz)z, Žā(z) = z."
